@jni That one is also possible. My thoughts here are (1) that `kernel_shape` suggests that a kernel that isn't a circle is possible, and (2) that it is not immediately obvious that `radius` controls the intensity dimension, and `kernel_shape` controls the spacial dimension. For (1) this can be made possible, but currently isn't; it's essentially moving from a spheroid to an ellipsoid as a structuring element. for (2) `radius` isn't quite accurate for the intensity dimension either, because the object being "rolled" is not the cap of a ball, but actually the cap of an ellipsis. Hence `radius` specifies the (co-)vertex of an ellipsis rather than a radius.

@lagru Yes, they would be required. The logic is (roughly) the following: We start with rolling a ball/sphere in the image, but this is not general, because the intensity dimension may have a different scale than the spacial dimensions of the image. Hence we "squish" the intensity dimension (current implementation [firefoxmetzger/scikit-image@730d809]); now we have a ball/circle in the spacial dimensions with a little cap on top for the intensity dimension. If we spin that around the intensity dimension the result is a spheroid. To make it even more general, there is no need for both spacial dimensions to be scaled in the same way (this is essentially @jni 's `kernel_shape` suggestion), and the resulting object we roll in the image is an ellipsoid. This needs me to do some thinking, because it changes the equation to compute the `sagitta` (not a fitting name anymore; need to think of a better one).

Going to nd-images with multiple color channels is relatively easy; we just repeat what we do for the one intensity dimension n times (bigger matrix multiplication). The question isn't so much if this is possible to implement, but if there is practical utility. What does it mean for a hyperellipsoid/hyperspheroid to be rolled around in a (color) image? Is the result still the background intensity?

